tr:name>FELLOW</gtr:name></gtr:role><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=ES%2FI035389%2F1"><gtr:id>64C7DA4E-8073-4108-BD74-457F117477C1</gtr:id><gtr:title>The educational and labour market expectations of adolescents and young adults</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/I035389/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>Completing higher education is becoming more expensive, with educational decisions typically made at age 18 having ever greater financial implications. It is therefore vital that young adults are well informed about the economic value of different degrees. But are young adults capable of making such rational assessments of the future, and do they hold enough information to make such financially complex decisions?&lt;/p>

&lt;p>This project shall tackle this issue by investigating whether men and women in their late teens and early twenties are realistic about the salary they will earn at various points in their future career. A related concern is that children from less fortunate households are under-represented amongst the undergraduate population. Some academics and policymakers suggest that children from disadvantaged backgrounds do not aspire to higher education, that they think it is 'not for the likes of them'. This project will also explore the educational plans of over 200,000 children from 33 developed countries to consider whether the low expectations of disadvantaged children are a greater barrier to higher education in the UK than in other industralised nations.&lt;br />&lt;br />&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2012-10-31</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2011-11-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>85125</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutput><gtr:description>Interview on Institute for Fiscal Studies website</gtr:description><gtr:id>38700CC9-0C98-4F3D-9A37-B7A6605D7958</gtr:id><gtr:outcomeId>r-9095217072.4935999c9e7b86</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:title>The socio-economic gradient in teenagers' reading skills</gtr:title><gtr:type>Film/Video/Animation</gtr:type><gtr:yearFirstProvided>2012</gtr:yearFirstProvided></gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutput></gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs><gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:description>The unrealistic educational expectations of high school pupils : is America exceptional</gtr:description><gtr:form>Participation in an activity, workshop or similar</gtr:form><gtr:id>54FF5D8B-4198-4379-8C92-315D